Concerning Eduardo's question: Now, if you work with a  Grothendieck=20
base topos =93as if it were the category of sets=94, you are forced to=20
specify which small category of finite sets you are using,    or not ?.

No, in the definition of an U-topos, E,  given in SGA 4, Expose IV, =A7 1=
,=20
it is required that E has an U-small (topologically) generating set of=20
objects.  Bu such a set  or, equivalently, full subcategory of E, is not=20
part of the data.

